Working on multiple projects and teams now for 10 years, it is really hard for me to keep quiet when yet another organization restructuring is on the way and the teams are to be split, spread, extended, shuffled, or whatever you want to call it.

## The team

{{< figure src="https://www.digitalmomblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/team-meme-for-work.jpg.webp" alt="" caption="" >}}

The best way I have worked up until this moment is the way of having every single role in a given team, no matter if the team is focused on a specific feature or a specific product. Let's give an example.

You are building an app that displays results from playing volleyball. You start building a team around that app and you need:

- Mobile Engineers - Android and iOS
- Web engineers
- Backend engineers
- Data analyst
- UI/UX designer
- Product owner
- If the team grows too fast - a SCRUM master to properly manage how loaded the team is with tasks
- Business person (on call) - someone who understands well certain requirements of the whole product. He is not a permanent part of your team but he has an overall understanding of every small piece that is part of your product. He can help you tie things together when you have lost your focus.

In short, this is all you need. I know it sounds a lot but this gives your team the independence they need to create, maintain and innovate with the functionalities you may not even know that you want. If you decide to go short without this fully functional team, you will always lose something.

Without a data analyst, you lose the exploration, usage, and usefulness of your features. You won't have an idea of "Does this thing that we spent months working on actually work?". Not only that but you also lose the ability for quick wins like "People who press this button seem to go through the whole user journey, maybe I should try making this button red".

Without a designer part of that team, you make the team stuck on certain UI decisions that may just not make sense. You are stuck on experimenting with small color changes here and there to make your app work in the best way possible.

Without engineers, you end up not having someone to create your product. Not only that but worse is to not have enough engineers. Without them, you risk people being stuck and waiting for engineers from other teams or even companies to have the spare time to implement the functionality in the way that you want it. And very often, they create it in such a fast manner that it does not meet the quality criteria of your team.

Without a PO ... I guess you, the reader, are the one, right? Otherwise, well, good luck with that.

## Focusing the army of engineers

Another really useful organizational thing is if you have many engineers that work with the same technology (for example Android ;)) just have regular weekly meetings with all of them. Let them share what they are working on, if they have any issues or just remind them of some basic rules about architecture and code design. It is very useful because the codebase will always grow bigger and bigger and there are times when you will figure out that different feature teams duplicate the same UI components. They don't focus on re-use because they don't know that a certain UI component was also developed by another team. This is also a result of ongoing miscommunication on all levels including design but by having these "guild" meetings you allow engineers to talk and find something that is already existing.

It was always useful for me to ask questions regarding code structure, functionality that I want to have, or a certain UI component that looks tricky. There is almost always someone who knows or who can help with the details.
